fields: We look for {{c1::molecular biomarkers}} in the aid of molecular diagnostics to find diseases.

What is the process to find molecular biomarkers while using molecular diagnostics? 
{{c1::Extraction}} --> {{c1::amplification}} --> {{c1::detection}}
{{c1::Noninvasive prenatal test}} looks for abnormalities in the fetus. Specifically it can tell you what number of chromosomes there are
What time period is the NIPT (noninvasive prenatal test) performed?
Who is recommended to get noninvasive prenatal testing?

A woman who will be aged 35 years or older at the time of delivery
A routine prenatal test result is positive for aneuploidy
A woman has a history of pregnancy with fetal trisomy
An ultrasound shows a fetal abnormality that could be caused by aneuploidy
A parent has a history of certain chromosomal abnormalities
Fetal DNA is naturally present in the blood and can be distinguished from the mom's blood by the {{c1::SNP signature}}

<font color="#ff0000">In her example she states that the mother is homozygous for an allele and has the genotype G/G and the father is homozygous for the same allele but has the genotype T/T. The fetus will therefore be heterzygous for the allele with the genotype G/T and can be distinguished from the mother's DNA due to this unique SNP signature. </font>

In NIPT the maternal blood is seperated into cellular (buffy coat) and liquid (plasma) fractions. Within the buffy coat their is mainly {{c1::maternal DNA}} present and within the plasma there is a {{c1::mixture of fetal DNA and maternal DNA}} present. Using SNP signatures we can identify which DNA belongs to the mother and which DNA belongs to the fetus.

To determine the amount of copies of a chromosome there is in fetal DNA using NIPT we look at {{c1::allele ratios. }}

In a normal amount of chromosomal copies the ratio will be {{c2::1:3 (unique fetal SNP:unique maternal SNP)}}

In an abnormal amount of chromosomal copies the ratio will be {{c2::1:4 (unique fetal SNP:unique maternal SNP)}}
The ratios hold true across many different unique SNPs on each chromosome.

If a patient is clinically determined to have Hereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer and microsatelite instability testing is {{c2::positive}} they could possibly have:

{{c1::Lynch syndrome}} - {{c3::positive mutation in germline mismatch repair protein, positive for colorectal cancer, risk of extracolonic cancers
}}
{{c1::Lynch-like syndrome}} - {{c4::negative germline mismatch repair protein, positive for colorectal cancer, risk of rare extracolonic cancers, relatively young age of onset. }}

If a patient is clinically determined to have Hereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer and microsatelite instability testing is {{c2::negative}} they could possibly have:

{{c1::Familial colorectal cancer type X (FCCTX)}} - {{c3::unknown or rare genetic causes, positive for colorectal cancer, no extracolonic cancers}}

{{c1::Polymerase proofreading polyposis}} - {{c4::POLE/POLD1 mutations, positive for colorectal cancer, adenomas, endometrial cancer}}

The {{c1::Opti-O-3}} is a {{c2::fatty acid biomarker}} test, which tests specifically for {{c3::cardiovascular disease risk}}.

The {{c4::AA:EPA}} ratio is the most accurate measure of "silent" or chronic inflammation.

How it is performed? {{c5::finger prick, the test will look for pro-inflammatory markers - prostaglandins, leukotrienes, thromboxanes}}

How does the Influenza/Flu test work?
1. {{c1::get a sample from patient}}
2. {{c2::Test searches for hemagglutinin and neuraminidase - surface glycoproteins on the surface of the virus.}}

Similar to pharmoacogenetics, we can sequence Hep. C virus's genome.
It has {{c1::4}} genotypes.
People with genotypes {{c2::2}} or {{c2::3}} respond much better to hep. c treatment than {{c3::1}} or {{c3::4}}.

How does a liquid biopsy for cancer work?
1. {{c1::get blood sample}}
2. {{c2::test for circulating cancerous biomarkers in patient's blood}}

Why might a blood liquid biopsy to test for cancer be better for your patient than a tissue biopsy?
{{c1::less invasive - avoid safety issues with puncturing organs
allow for personalized medicine by sequencing their DNA}}

How does a liquid saliva biopsy work?
1. {{c1::get patient saliva sample}}
2. {{c2::use MANY tests to determine presence of exosome-like microvesicles unique to cancers}}

What types of cancer can be found by saliva liquid biopsy?
1. {{c1::lung}} cancer
2. {{c2::pancreatic}} cancer
3. {{c3::breast}} cancer
4. {{c4::gastric}} cancer
Not sure if she wants us to know the actual biomarkers of each cancer, but I put the slides here if that ends up being the case

Cancers contain many epigenetic changes, specifically {{c1::methylated cysteine}}, supressing transcription, found along the region of tumor supressor genes. These epigenetic changes can be looked at by using samples of the patient's blood or samples of circulating tumor cells.
Looking at epigenetic information in cancer patients helps develop personalized medicine.

The {{c2::radioallergosorbent
test (RAST)}} can be used to looke at {{c1::antigen antibody complex}} to diagnose allergies.
Patients with atopic allergic diseases such as atopic asthma, atopic dermatitis, and hay fever have been shown to exhibit increased {{c1::total immunoglobulin E (IgE)}} levels in blood.

fields:
Stem cell therapy procedures harvest tissues from 3 places:
1. {{c2::adipose}}
2. {{c3::bone marrow}}
3. {{c4::platelet-rich plasma
}}
For the achilles tendon patient, all the doctors did was {{c1::inject this stuff into the damaged tissues}}

What procedure steps do you take to get fat-derived stem cells?
1. {{c1::liposuction procedure at abdominal area (usually)}}.
2. Put in centrifuge
3. "{{c4::SVF}}" pellet contains the stem cells we want
These stem cells are taken from the {{c2::patient::someone else or the patient?}} and then infused back into them {{c3::48}} hours later

What procedures steps do you take to get bone marrow stem cells?
1. {{c1::Get marrow (with needle aspiration) via iliac crest and proximal tibia below knee}}
2. {{c2::spin in centrifuge}}

The main types of injuries that would be useful to use bone marrow stem cells are {{c3::orthopedic-related injuries (mainly - see list below)}}

What are the steps to take to get a PRP (platelet-rich plasma) stem cell?
1. {{c2::Draw 30-60 mm blood from vein in arm}}
2. {{c3::Centrifuge}}

These stem cells are MOST useful in patients with {{c1::acute or chronic osteoarthritic pains and many tendons injuries/inflammations}}
For all stem cell types to be used, you simply inject at site of injury/pain. Growth factors in those areas tell the cells what to turn into

{{c4::Junctional epidermolysis bullosa}} is a condition associated with symptoms of {{c1::skin/mucous membrane fragility, blistering with little to no trauma}}. 
There is a defect in the {{c3::LAMB3}} protein, which is responsible for {{c2::holding epidermis/dermis to the basal layer}}.

It is classified into two categories. 
{{c5::Herlitz}} is more severe and usually lethal.
{{c5::Non-herlitz}} is less severe and non-lethal

What are the limitations to skin replacement stem cell therapy from junctional epidermolysis bullosa?
1. {{c1::you can still induce cancer}}
2. {{c2::we don't know if this can work in adults - children's stem cell population are have a higher renewal potential than in adults}}
What is the process called when a cell becomes specialized in order to perform a specialized function?
What are the possible changes a cell can have when it undergoes differentiation?
{{c1::Senescent cells}} are no longer capable of dividing, although they are still metabolically active.
<font color="#ff0000">Hits the limit for # of divisions it is able to undergo. </font>
Most of the differentiated cells in adult tissues are suspended in {{c1::G<sub>0</sub>}}<sub> </sub>and cannot re-enter the cell cycle. They are receiving no growth signals.
What differentiated adult tissues are able to re-enter the cell cycle if needed?
What signaling is required for differentiated adult tissues to re-enter the cell cycle?

In tissues there is a subset of adult stem cells are {{c1::multipotent}}. These cells can help {{c2::maintain tissue homeostasis}} after somatic cells are lost to injury or normal cell death, helping to maintain the cell death and proliferation balance.
<font color="#ff0000">Cancers are hypothesized to start in these stem cells. </font>
Subpopulations of stem cells usually exist at the {{c1::basal layer}} in a {{c2::niche}}, or distinct microenvironment.

Within a subpopulation when a stem cells divides it leads to the production of two cells: 
{{c2::One remains a stem cell}}
{{c1::One becomes a transit-amplfying cell which is a rapidly proliferating intermediate cell that is capable of further differentiating. }}
{{c1::Wnt}} which is secreted by {{c2::fibroblasts under GI crypts}} regulates the differentiation process of
As you work your way up the crypt you become more specialized.

How do adult stem cells know when to produce a transit-amplifying cell and how do transit-amplfying cells know to further differentiate? 

{{c1::You need a specific ligand to activate a receptor and downstream cause an increase in transcription factors which turn on a set of genes to produce a specific cellular program. }}

{{c1::OCT4}} and {{c1::SOX2}} are two transcription factors that maintain the embryonic stem cell state. For example if you take a fibroblast and add these transcription factors you can revert it back to a pluripotent stem cell state.
OCT4 and SOX2 transcription factors can also be controlled using epigenetics, specifically they are {{c1::methylated}} during cell differentiation.
<font color="#ff0000">Methylation turns the genes off, letting the cell differentiate instead of reverting back and becoming a pluripotent stem cell. </font>
A cell is considered {{c1::terminally differentiated}} when it cannot be specialized any further.
As we travel upwards the cells get further differentiated
As we travel upwards the cells get further differentiated
As we travel upwards the cells get further differentiated
As we travel upwards the cells get further differentiated
{{c1::PPARgamma}} is the transcription factor that heterodimerizes with {{c2::RXR (retinoid X receptor)}} to initiate tryglyceride storage at adipocytes.

{{c1::Transdifferentiation}} is the differentiation between white and brown adipose tissues. There is no cell division involved. 

White to brown adipose transformation is known as browning phenomenon and is induced by {{c2::cold temperatures and/or chronic physical exercise (such as in runners)}}

Brown to white transformation occurs when there is {{c3::caloric excess. }}

{{c1::Endochondral ossification}} uses {{c2::hyaline cartilage}} as a template to then be replaced by bone. This process makes bones at the
base of the skull and long bones.

Intramembranous ossification follows four steps:
(a) {{c1::Mesenchymal cells group into clusters, differentiate into osteoblasts, and ossification centers form.}} 
(b) {{c2::Secreted osteoid traps osteoblasts, which then become osteocytes.}}
(c) {{c3::Trabecular matrix and periosteum form.}} 
(d) {{c4::Compact bone develops superficial to the trabecular bone, and crowded blood vessels condense into red bone marrow.}}
<font color="#ff0000">Considered more of a de novo synthesis</font>
Skeletal muscle is differentiated by the transcription factor {{c1::MyoD}}
{{c1::Satellite cells}} are the adult muscle stem cells and after injury they can help muscle cells differentiate into skeletal muscle.
Does cardiac muscle contain any adult stem cells?
No! Myocytes have limited repair capabilities and the damaged cardiac muscle ends up being replaced with fibrous connective tissue (scarring).
Which muscle type can undergo hyperplasia and hypertrophic repair?

When Ca++ channels in a bouton are activated by an action potential, Ca++ enters the cell and binds to {{c1::synaptotagmin}} which, in turn, alters the function of {{c2::vSNARE}} proteins so that they bind to {{c2::tSNARE}} proteins and cause fusion of a synaptic vesicle with the presynaptic membrane. Neurotransmitter molecules released from vesicles diffuse into the synaptic cleft to bind to postsynaptic receptor proteins. Other postsynaptic proteins such as {{c3::neuroligin}} bind to presynaptic {{c3::neurexins}} to keep the synaptic membranes in close apposition.
{{c1::Choroid plexus}} are modified ependymal cells that produce CSF.

{{c1::DNA repair mechanisms}} are working at full capacity early in life but as we age they break down over time.
What repairs small spontaneous lesions in DNA?
Base excision repair.

{{c1::Nucleotide excision repair (NER)}} repairs bulky lesions in DNA. It is a multienzyme complex that scans for distoritions in the double helix structure and once it finds the distortion it cleaves the phosphodiester backbone on either side.
{{c1::Mismatch repair (MMR)}} corrects DNA mismatches generated by DNA polymerase.
MtuS and MutL bind to the mismatched base and direct the excision of the DNA between the single strand DNA break and the mismatch.

When there is too much damage to DNA it causes DNA polymerases to stall when replicating thus there are 10+ backup polymerases that can take over the polymerase activity. These polymerases are {{c1::less accurate and are just guessing what the original sequence was.:: more or less accurate? }}

RNA polymerase II stalls when lesions are present on the template strand and directs repair machinery to the lesion site. The RNA polymerase is remodeled by {{c1::transcription-coupled repair}} and the lesion is able to be repaired and RNA polymerase restarted.

Double stranded DNA breaks are signs of more severe DNA damage and can occur due to {{c1::radiation, errors, and oxidation}}. There are two repair mechanisms involved to fix double stranded DNA breaks: {{c1::Nonhomologous end joining}} and {{c2::homologous recombination. }}

3 things that contribute to successful aging:
1. {{c1::avoiding disease and disability}}
2. {{c2::social networks}}
3. {{c3::cognitive and physical health}}
One trait that is common to ALL super old people is {{c1::optimism}}

Our average life span has been lengthened via:
1. {{c1::increased early survival}}
2. {{c2::increased late survival}}
3. {{c3::delaying senescence}}

Age studies use 3 study types:
{{c1::longitudinal}} = follow same subjects over a long period of time
{{c1::cross-sectional}} = on one occasion, compare subjects of different ages
{{c1::cross-sequential}} = assess subjects in a cross-sectional sample more than once

4 theories of aging:
1. {{c1::oxidative damage}} - {{c2::free radicals increase as we age and modify DNA/proteins}}
2. {{c3::telomeres}} - {{c6::telomere length decreases as we age}}
3. {{c4::genetic alterations with aging}}
4. {{c5::mitochondrial aging}} - {{c7::they have no repair mechanism, increased ROS, decreased ETC}}

Endogenous defense mechanisms from oxidative stress:
1. {{c1::SOD}} converts O2- (radical) ---> H2O2
2. {{c2::Glutathione peroxidase}} converts H2O2 ---> H2O

Genes that affect aging:
1. {{c1::stress-resistance genes}}
2. {{c2::inflammation genes}}
3. {{c3::slowing metabolism genes (like IGF)}}

{{c2::Progeria}} is a mutation in {{c1::Werner's codes for DNA helicase}}.
Comes in 2 flavors:
1. {{c3::Werner's}} syndrome (adult-onset)
and
2. {{c3::Hutchinson-Gilford}} syndrome (juvenile-onset)

What can we do about aging?
1. {{c1::caloric restriction}} - gene expression more {{c2::stable}} in monkeys
2. {{c3::Antioxidants}} - prevent {{c6::oxidative species reactions in body}}
3. {{c4::Exercise}} - {{c5::duh}}
{{c2::Rapamycin}} and {{c2::Acarbose}} are both drugs that have been shown to be useful in {{c1::anti-aging}}!

What do you do when the preceptor says:

Cervical

1. Have pt supine
2. AGR screening using the articualr pillars of C2-C7 and the occiput to screen OA
3. Diagnose ONE segment, either OA or typical cervical

What do you do when the preceptor says:

Thoracic

1. Find the AGR, make sure to check both sides of the spine
2. Verbalize AGR
3. Diagnose a Type I or Type II segment

What do you do when the preceptor says:

Lumbar

1. AGR screening, make sure to go down both sides and verbalize findings
2. Diagnose a Type I (3 or more) or Type II segment

What do you do when the preceptor says:

Pelvis

1. Have pt standing, facing away from you
2. Find PSIS and contact just inferiorly and provide a gentle superior force. 
3. Ask pt to bend forward adn follow the PSIS's with your thumbs
4. Verbalize the side that moves first and farthest!!
5. Have pt lay supine on table and reset their hips (make them bridge and PASSIVELY move their feet back down) !!!!
6. Place hands over ASIS and add a posterior-inferior vector, I would verbalize this vector direction!
7. Verbalize the side that when compressed the opposite hip moves into your hand the quickest (hopefully that makes sense if not think about it however works for you)

What do you do when the preceptor says:

Sacrum

1. Have pt seated and FEET ON THE GROUND
2. Contact just inferior to the PSIS and provide a slight superior force
3. Have pt bend forward and track which side goes first and farthest
4. Verbalize side that was lateralized!!
5. Then have pt lay prone on the table for the spring test
6. Palpate the sacrum and provide an anterior-inferior force and determine if there is spring
7. Have the pt come onto their elbows and recheck - if negative the spring will be more noticeable. (This is how it says to do it in the competency checklist so I would do it this way unless noted otherwise from a tutor or someone)

What do you do when the preceptor says:

Ribs

1. Have pt lay supine and check the first rib
2. Screen ribs 2-5 parasternally - pump handle ribs
3. Screen ribs 6-10 laterally - bucket handle ribs
4. Screen ribs 11-12 - caliper ribs
5. Using BITE mneumonic find the key rib and dx the the group of ribs involved in the dysfunction

**The side that has the most motion is normal

What do you do when the preceptor says:

Shoulder

1. Have the pt perform active ROM in all 6 planes (flexion, extension, abduction, adduction, internal rotation, and external rotation) --> Verbalize findings as the pt goes through these motions!
2. Then check integrity of the supraspinatous by having the pt perform the empty can test or drop arm test

What do you do when the preceptor says:

Elbow

1. Screen the carrying angle- verbalize any findings
2. Have the pt do active pronation and supination - verbalize any findings
3. Diagnose the radial head first using tranlational motions
4. Can check diagnosis using passive pronation and supination: Dx will either be anterior radial head or posterior radial head. Remember P's go together!

What do you do when the preceptor says:

Hip

1. With pt supine test flexion, abduction, adduction, internal rotation, and external rotation --> Verbalize any findings where the pt is restricted in motion!
2. Have pt lay prone now and test extension --> verbalize findings
3. Next have pt return back to supine and scoot their butt towards the end with legs hanging off at a 90 degress angle to test for tight psoas muscles using the Thomas test.
4. Ask the pt to bring one knee towards their chest and note the change in teh opposite leg. Repeat on other leg. Positive if the other leg rises off the table!

What do you do when the preceptor says:

Knee

1. Screen both knees for dysfunction by having pt squat --> verbalize any findings
2. Have pt lay supine on table and flex the knee that was deemed dysfunctional.
3. Sit on the foot to stabilize the lower leg and find the fibular head.
4. Provide a posterior-medial force and anterior-lateral force and dx the fibular head.
